  "text": "2 DSA mechanism and synchrotron radiation 2.1 The brief review of the DSA fundamentals Fermi proposed in his crucial paper [CITATION_1] ) the way of acceleration of charged particles to the energy of cosmic rays (CRs) and derived that the energy gain in one collision between a particle and the magnetic perturbation to be ∝ (u/v) 2 , where u is the velocity of magnetic perturbation, and v is the velocity of high-energy particle. In the interstellar case, the mechanism proposed by Fermi is not very efficient but the fact that particles can gain energy in collisions with the irregularities of the magnetic field is at the basis of all acceleration theories. Later, when the Fermi model was established as the ideal starting point, this original mechanism of particle acceleration was called the second order Fermi acceleration mechanism (also known as Fermi 2 acceleration). On the other hand, DSA is the first order Fermi acceleration mechanism (also known as Fermi 1 acceleration) where during the collision between a charged particle and the magnetic perturbation (in the case of DSA the magnetic perturbation is represented by a magnetized collisionless shock discontinuity)",
